  "texts": [
    "Without a nonlinear activation function, the parameters are found with a least-squares regression.",
    "This was demonstrated for PINNs in [293].",
    "Instead of only learning the last layer, the problem can be split into a non-linear and a linear regression problem, which are solved separately [294], such that the full expressivity of NNs is retained.",
    "Applications to forward problemsPINNs have been applied to various PDEs (see [229][230][231] for an overview).",
    "Forward problems can, for example, be found in solid mechanics [284,295,296], fluid mechanics [297][298][299][300][301][302][303][304], and thermomechanics [305,306]."
